When this car was being pick up in a set of cars at the WLE Waco Siding in Jewett, OH and the conductor was walking his train, he noticed car GATX 56657 leaking liquid from the bottom of the bottom outlet valve.  He notified the WLE Dispatcher who then called myself, John Vergis Environmental Officer for WLE.  When I arrived, I found that oil was leaking from the bottom outlet valve cap.  Upon looking further I found that the 2 inch plug in the cap was loose.  I loosened the plug a little more to see if the leak would slow down or get worse to see if maybe the valve itself was defective.  The leak did slow down so I took the plug out and then inspected the valve for any leaking through on the valve seal.  The valve was not leaking.  The oil that was leaking out was trapped in the valve nozzle.  I cleaned the old thread sealant off the cap plug and put new sealant on the threads and then installed the plug and tightened it.  I then released the car for service.
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: On 08/02/2017 at 0952 hours personnel in the CSXT Rocky Mount yard discovered PPNX 1078, a loaded tank car of Ammonia Anhydrous leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and (Rocky Mount 911 Operator 6607, NRC, North Carolina Emergency Management and CHEMTRECT) were notified CHEMTREC Report # 2017-0802-00213 . Marion Environmental, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found that the tank car was overloaded and the car was venting from the pressure relief valve. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Tracey Smith Ph#847-208-2727). Contractor personnel fixed the problem reduced the load.  The car was transferred. Once the car was transferred the PRV was further examined and found that the o-ring had been pinched caused by the actuation of the PRV. The deformed o-ring was removed, replaced and the pressure relief valve was re-qualified. This incident did not require a special switching move.

column168: a 10 gallon release of UN2014 "Hyperclean Boost" from a 55 gal poly drum in trailer # 3174329 at the XPO terminal XCU. The spill was the result of improper bracing by the previous terminal XSL as it arrived unsecured and fell over during unloading. The caller advised that one of the dock employees was exposed to the material and was in the process of washing his eyes. The XPO supervisor onsite was contacted and confirmed the employee is doing much better and will not be admitted to the hospital. An environmental contractor was dispatched and cleaned the impacted areas and over packed the damaged drum. All wastes were staged on site pending disposition. No drains, soils or waterways were impacted by the release

a 5 oz release of UN1993 "Chemtrend MOC 10020 mold release" from a 330 gal metal tote on the dock inside the terminal. The spill was the result of an apparent defective dome gasket seal on the top of the tote as it arrived leaking once it was removed from the trailer. An environmental contractor was dispatched and aligned and secured the gasket. Upon agitation, no further release occurred.

column168: At 1500 Rich with the UMV terminal contacted ERTS in regards to an empty leaking 500 lb. cylinder of nitrogen. it was reported that when trailer 3177448 was received dock workers found 1 of three cylinders was leaking from a valve. Rich reported that they have already placed the container in a clear area away from people and where letting the tank relieve pressure. At this time ERTS considers this as a non-emergency situation due to the product being an inert gas and there is no one in the area. ERTS estimates the nearest contractor to be 60+ miles out with a 2 hour ETA. by the time a contractor was to arrive the cylinder would be empty and the contractor would have a 4 hour minimum to respond. There was no release to the environment and there for the release will not require reporting. Since there is no waste there will be no need for a titan entry either.

He drove approximately 4 miles to mile marker 8 on I-26 and a passing motorist flagged him down, saying his trailer was leaking. Driver pulled to the right shoulder and found the rear clean-out cap was missing. The local fire department arrived on scene but took no action because what product had spilled out was evaporated. The shipper brought our driver a replacement clean-out cap to the scene. Driver installed the cap and returned to shipper and had the exterior of trailer washed. He then proceeded on his way.
column169: Driver had the trailer washed out prior to loading and swears after his inspection the clean-out cap was there and secure. We have asked the driver to make sure he inspects the trailer after loading before leaving a plant to insure all domes and caps are in place and secure.

column168: At approximately 1850hrs CT, trainyard personnel reported a strong rotten egg odor from GATX 53274 which was a residue class 8 pgII UN1760 Corrosive Liquids N.O.S. column168: PACKAGE WAS RECEIVED AT OUR SHIPPING DOCK FROM A CUSTOMER WITH A COCKPIT VOICE/DATA RECORDER (CVR) INSIDE THE PACKAGE. THE 90 DAY BEACON ON THE CVR CONTAINS 1.75G LITHIUM METAL CONTENT SO THIS WAS A LITHIUM METAL BATTERY PACKAGED IN EQUIPMENT SHIPMENT. PACKAGE HAD NO MARKINGS THAT IT WAS A DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SHIPMENT. OUR SHIPPING DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL UNPACKAGED THE UNIT AND DELIVERED THE UNIT TO OUR REPAIR DEPARTMENT. WE NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER THEY SHIPPED A DANGEROUS GOOD WITHOUT THE PROPER LABELS AND DOCUMENTATION AND THAT THEY NEEDED TO REMEDY THIS IN THE FUTURE AND THAT UNIVERSAL AVIONICS WAS REQUIRED TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THERE WAS NO RELEASE.
column169: OUR PERSONNEL HAVE RECEIVED TRAINING ON RECOGNIZING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARRIVING AT OUR DOCK WITH ISSUES AND TO NOTIFY MANAGEMENT WHEN AN INCIDENT OCCURS. WE PROVIDED ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO RECOGNIZE WHEN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ARRIVES WITHOUT THE APPROPRIATE MARKINGS OR DOCUMENTATION AND NO RELEASE AND TO IMMEDIATELY REPORT IT TO MANAGEMENT SO WE CAN CAPTURE ALL THE APPROPRIATE INFORMATION IN ORDER TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. WE HAVE ALSO NOTIFIED CUSTOMERS AND DEALERS THROUGH NEWSLETTERS, A NOTICE ON OUR CUSTOMER WEBSITE AND A SERVICE BULLETIN ABOUT RESHIPPING THIS PARTICULAR PRODUCT FOR REPAIRS AND THE NEED TO SHIP AS DANGEROUS GOODS/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

column168: While loading a 55 gallon steel drum into a Veolia vehicle at the Veolia in-transit facility, paint material spilled from the lid of the container due to a missing gasket. There were no injuries. There was an estimated amount of 3 gallons spilled of paint related material. Event occurred for less than 30 seconds. Veolia employees cleaned and re-containerized spilled paint related material.
column169: Veolia employees immediately reported the incident and submitted an incident report to the Veolia Environmental Health and Safety (EHS) department. EHS and employees reviewed incident and determined the need to improve our container inspection process before moving and handling drums. Inspection improvements have been implemented and are currently being performed prior to moving or handling hazardous material packagings.

column168: ON 08/02/2017 AT 0455 IT WAS REPORTED THAT Q38831 DERAILED CARS 33-65 IN HYNDMAN PENNSYLVANIA, CAR CBTX 781553, LOAD OF PROPANE, WAS BREACHED AND CAUGHT FIRE. THE PUNCTURE MEASURED ABOUT 3.25 INCHES IN LENGTH LOCATED AT THE 3 O’CLOCK POSITION ON THE A-R END. TWO OTHER CARS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ALSO LOST PRODUCT. UTLX 643949, A TANK CAR LOAD OF ASPHALT, HAD THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE SHEARED OFF, THE OPERATING HANDLE WAS BENT AND THE 5082, A LOADED TANK CAR OF MOLTEN SULFUR, SUFFERED A 7 FOOT TRANSVERSE SHELL TEAR IN THE RIGHT CORNER OF THE CAR. THE BOTTOM SUSTAINED A 32 X 18 INCH PUNCTURE MID-WAY BETWEEN THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND THE A-END OF THE CAR. ITDX 5082 LOST THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE CAR, 13,229 GALLONS. DO TO THE FIRE FROM THE CAR CBTX 781553, A COMMUNITY EVACUATION WAS INITIATED INVOLVING APPROXIMATELY 1000 CITIZENS FOR APPROXIMATELY 78.5 HOURS. THE CSX MAINLINE TRACK WAS CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY 78 HRS AND 35 MINUTES.
column169: (ATTRI: DERAILMENT CAUSED PUNCTURE. SEE NARRATIVE)

column168: The trailer is an end dump. The material is required to be control flowed off the trailer into a hopper. The tailgate is held in place by eye bolts that manually lock the door closed, forcing the material out of the grain door located in the main door.  Apparently part of the load stuck in the front of the trailer, and when it fell loose, it hit the tailgate door with enough force to strip the eye bolts, allowing the remainder of the product to spill onto the ground.
column169: Recommended changes are as follows:    Better maintenance on the eye bolts.  Retrain the driver to be more aware of the position of the load in the trailer during unloading.  Receiver to have barriers put in place to prevent overflow situations.

column168: Clean Harbors warehouse employee was off-loading a van trailer when he noticed a liquid material on the floor of the trailer.  After removing additional containers, the employee found 2 pallets that had 12 boxes each shrink-wrapped w/4-1g plastic containers inside the boxes leaning against 2 other pallets.  The employee immediately applied speedi-dri to the spill area and then removed the 2 pallets from the van trailer.  Additional personnel cleaned up the spill area. There were 37-1g containers placed in 3-85g overpacks. The 3 overpacks and clean up material were sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: It was determined that the pallets were not loaded correctly in the van causing the pallets to shift and eventually caused the plastic containers to leak.  The warehouse employees responsible for loading the vans were reminded that all containers needed to be loaded and secured properly so that any type of container would not be allowed to shift during transit.

column168: ERTS received a call from Landstar to report a spill. It was reported at 1530 ET, driver Roberto of truck #417761 / trailer # 693501 was delivering to a Sysco location when the shipment was rejected due to several damaged "wet" containers of UN1824 Sodium Hydroxide damaged inside of the trailer, no material released outside of the cardboard container. ERTS dispatched D&H Petroleum for a response. Contractor arrived on site and confirmed only 1-2 Gallon container of material was damaged releasing approximately 10 ounces of material to the cardboard container. The entire shipment was rejected and all containers were overpacked into UN Rated Containers for disposal.

THE SHIPMENT WAS FOUND LEAKING IN THE SORT. UPON OPENING THE BOX WE FOUND THREE CARDBOARD BOXES EACH CONTAINING ONE GLASS BOTTLE OF PERFUME. THERE WAS KRAFT LIKE PAPER FOR CUSHIONING AND DUNNAGE, BUT NO ABSORBENT IN VIOLATION OF 49 CFR 173.27(E) OR A BARRIER BAG IN VIOLATION OF 49 CFR 173.27 (E) (3). THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION MEM SECFO HAZMAT MANAGER STAN ATCHELL WAS NOTIFIED ELECTRONICALLY.

column168: On August 26, 2017, XPO Logistics (XSW Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN1263, CarboCoat 115 VOC, 3, PG II, (PRO#371740703) release. column168: This incident pertains to a release of a UN1083 TRIMETHYLAMINE, ANHYDROUS. There was (4) cylinders discovered damaged and approximately 20 gas pounds of this product released. This release was caused by improper loading by the previous terminal. Freight shifted during transit and ruptured the pressure relief valves of the cylinders. This release was contained. No soils, drains, or waterways were impacted. There were no reported injuries or exposures. There were no reported fires, threats of fire, evacuations or threats of evacuations. A certified environmental contractor conducted response operations for this release.

column162: SVP HEALTH, SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: While conducting his Post-Trip inspection, the driver noticed free liquid on top of one of the drums in his shipment. Upon inspection, a small amount of liquid had leaked past the bung and was contained on the top of the drum. After donning appropriate PPE, the liquid was removed with absorbent pads and the bungs re-tightened to the manufacturers specification. The waste generated from the clean up was properly contained and will be shipped to an approved disposal site.
column169: Drivers have been counseled to always check closures for proper installation and that they are tightened to the drum manufacturers specifications.

column168: Driver was transferring Delpac 2020 from an IBC located on the truck into a customer's storage tank.  A leak was discovered during the transfer.  The leak was located at where the valve threads into the IBC bottle.  This was behind the discharge valve.  Once discovered; the spill was contained in a drip bucket.  Approximately 5 gals of product was spilled onto the customer gravel drive-way.  Spill was contained and cleaned-up.  No discharge into waterway, surface waters, sewage or storm drains.
column169: Exploring alternate method of discharging IBCs while on truck, discontinue use the bottom outlet discharge of the IBC.  Will pump product out of the top of the IBC instead.  Also reviewed inspection activites with contractor and will replace valves with worn threads every 2.5 years.

column168: The driver was delivering a load of ethanol to a terminal in Charlotte, NC. He had driven this road before and said it was a typical delivery. He stated he was not speeding, weather was good, and he was wide awake feeling good. He was in a slight curve to the left when he felt a slight tug and the tanker and truck rolled over into the ditch. Another HOT-Z driver came along right after the accident and was able to get the driver out of the truck.  Mr. Dover also called the HOT-Z General Manager who came to the scene and aided in the restoration.  No other vehicles were involved and emergency personnel and Geological Resources, Inc. were called to the scene to handle the clean-up. The fire department was able to plug the hole and keep the leakage to a minimum. The driver was taken to the hospital and released later that day.
column169: Continued training for drivers on rollover prevention through insurance company programs.      The road in this accident had a low shoulder which may have been the tug the driver felt.  Eliminating these "low shoulders" especially on curves might help prevent accidents.

column168: This was a hazardous waste shipment from a TSDF to another TSDF for final disposal of the material.  Originally the drums were from Manifest 010981251FLE. Two drums were discovered to be leaking in a trailer during transit check by the driver.  Less than two gallons of the material leaked and was contained to the trailer.  Response crew was called out to respond and overpack.  Drums were inspected for leak cause and it was determined that the two that leaked had only partial gaskets in the lids.
column169: Original shipper should check lids for gaskets before offering for transport.  Internally driver should also look to see if lids look properly seated or are they too low in the rings indicating there could be a missing gasket.

column162: SVP HEALTH SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: During routine facility inspections, a trailer was found leaking on the 10 day concrete containment pad. Facility personnel immediately notified management and dispatched the internal response team; they were already on site and able to respond immediately. The trailer and concrete were impacted by the release; no soil, no water ways and no storm drains were impacted. In proper personal protective equipment, the ER team assessed the site and trailer. The ER team made entry into the trailer and located the leaking drum. The compromised drum was cracked at the bottom. Upon inspection of this drum, it was determined that the drums rating had expired. This release is a direct result of improper container selection. This drum was placed into a UN specification rated salvage drum. The ER team thoroughly decontaminated the trailer and site. All waste generated from the cleanup was put into an appropriate UN specification rated drums, labeled and marked accordingly and send to its final disposal destination without further incident. Tom Ball of Utah Department of Environmental Quality was notified and state report #13100 was generated.
column169: Driver was counseled and retrained on UN specification and container inspection via online company modules and by reviewing, and then presenting company talking points, to peer group. Generator was notified of release and of the importance of UN specification ratings and proper container selection prior to offering container into transportation. Account Manager for the generator also reviewed how to read a UN rating on a drum and offered to supply new drums as an ongoing corrective measure to ensure this would not happen again.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: Event # 65807    Driver arrived at Consignee.  Consignee does all the unloading.  During the unloading process, the emergency shut off valve popped releasing product onto side of trailer.    The emergency valve is a breakaway and closes the internal valve. They are known to fail but usually it is caused by excessive pressure when putting too much pressure on the internal valve jack.
column169: Consignee washed off trailer and completed the unloading process without further incident.

column168: On 08/04/17, a loader was in the process of loading Hydroflourosilic acid on trailer 7900 for Pencco. The load was coming out of railcar GATX 63219. This was the second half of a split load. The loader overloaded the trailer by 4 inches and needed to unload some product back into the railcar. The loader started loading product back into the railcar. After several minutes of unloading the trailer, product started releasing from the air valve fitting that was setup on the railcar. The loader then shut the air valve off. Product then started coming out from the flange of the rupture disk housing. Its estimated 30 gallons of product was released and impacted the ballast. The Massachusetts DEP was notified of the release. The DEP incident number is 2-20272. The local fire department visited the terminal in response to a call from the state. They departed the terminal with no further findings. Clean Harbors was contacted and arrived at the terminal at 5:50 PM. Clean Harbors filled two drums with ballast and used one bag of lime to neutralize the product   Upon further investigation it was learned that the loader and the driver were working together to complete this premium service transfer. The loader was on top of the railcar while the driver was sticking the trailer. The loader insists that the driver was not paying attention to the transfer and overloaded the trailer. The transfer was stopped and the loader attempted to put product back into the railcar without seeking assistance. The railcar was overloaded at that time.
column169: 1. Covered the importance of using work instructions and communication to monitor loads to all terminals in the network 2.Retrain all employees 3. column168: On 08/22/17 at 1727 hours personnel in the CSXT Pascagoula Yard discovered an unknown car of anhydrous ammonia to be leaking.  After several hours of CSX Hazmat, CSX Hazmat contractors, and fire department personnel inspecting the area tank car CPDX102008, a residue tank car of anhydrous ammonia, was found to be leaking from the pressure plate. The car was isolated and the shipper Mississippi Export Railroad and Consignee Chevron Products were notified.  Mississippi Export RR and Chevron advised that the car last came from Helena Chemcial in New Carlisle, IN and provided that waybill. Specialized Professional Services Inc. (SPSI), Hepaco, and USES, a CSXT response contractor, were dispatched to the scene.  CSX Hazmat and SPSI found CPDX102008 to be leaking from the pressure plate. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the consignee, Chevron Products (Billy Burrell 228-990-3983) who advised he would update the shipper (their customer Helena Chemical).  The shipper of record on the CSXT waybill, Mississippi Export Railroad, Matt Fogle (228-627-6777) was also updated and provided that Helena Chemical was the actual shipper.      2(4+9+5) x (3+4) = 252      Pascagoula, MS – 08/22/17 – CPDX102008 – Anhydrous Ammonia

column168: 08/23/2017 1835 EST - Cole Clark with Koch Trucking reported 20-gallons of UN2794, Batteries, wet, filled with acid,8, PGIII released from an unknown number of 2,850-pound forklift batteries. Charles stated that (8) 2,850-pound batteries are on the trailer. The release has impacted the trailer floor and asphalt beneath the trailer. The incident occurred at Erie Island Travel Plaza; 1012 N Sandusky Co Rd 260, Clyde, OH 43410. After entering the trailer and inspecting the freight the contractor stated (1) 2,850-pound forklift battery was not properly secured and fell over in transit causing the release. Sodium Bicarbonate was used to neutralize the impacted asphalt and trailer floor. Contractor containerized 1-55 gallon poly drum of waste and removed from site for proper disposal. No soils, waterways, or drains were impacted.

column162: SVP HEALTH SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: During routine facility inspection, facility personnel noticed a slight release on a cubic yard box affixed to a pallet, sitting in containment. Personnel donned the proper personal protective equipment and placed absorbent mats under the release. The pallet and outside of the cubic yard box were impacted by the release; no soil, water or storm drains were impacted. A response crew was dispatched to assist. A third party technician arrived onsite, donned proper PPE and began assessing the site. The cubic yard box was repackaged into a new cubic yard box. All waste associated with the cleanup was put into appropriate UN specification rated containers, properly labeled and marked and sent onto final destination without further incident. During the response it was determined that a nail from the pallet had punctured the cubic yard box, causing the release. No further reporting was needed.
column169: Facility personnel were counseled and retrained on container preparation and selection, utilizing intercompany training guidelines and talking points. Management utilized these topics to present the findings in a weekly branch safety meeting. Furthermore, the generator was notified and the importance of inspecting pallets used for transportation of waste was discussed, as was shipping container selection and preparation.

column169: USE 8 KEYS AND HAND TO SURFACE METHODS. SHIPPER SHOULD USE CAP GUARDS TO KEEP CAPS CLOSED.

column168: DISCOVERED THE PACKAGING ON THE FLOOR UNDER A BELT. FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE PACKAGE WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP ARE FOR PROCESSING AND DISPOSAL.

column168: RESPONDER DISPATCHED TO A LEAKING HAZMAT, AT BAY 164, IN THE EAST PRIMARY. UPON ARRIVAL, RESPONDER UTILIZED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET TO CONTAINERIZE THE LEAKING PACKAGE. NO LIQUID WAS ON THE FLOOR. THE PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO THE DMP CAGE, FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. INFORMATION WAS COLLECTED ON THE PACKAGE AND ENTERED INTO ETT. On August 31, 2017, during the examination of export documents offered for transport. The carrier (Seaboard Marine) noticed on an invoice that container SMLU795571 was carrying non-hazardous as well as hazardous cargo (UN 1077, Air, Propylene). The container was on terminal grounds at the time we (Seaboard Marine) notice that undeclared hazardous cargoes had been loaded. We immediately placed a HOLD on the container and prohibited future movement. The shipper was asked to provide the proper documentation describing all the hazardous materials inside of the container. The same day, upon receipt, review, and acceptance of the shipping papers, the container was placarded accordingly and afterward released for transportation

column168: Event # 65905-1..      Driver at the consignee unloading. He had shut down the internal and external valves and shut off the air supply to the tank wagon. He disconnected the hose from the tank wagon. This is the consignee's hose and it goes from their tank directly to the trailer. He went to disconnect the hose and there was a backflow and it was very fast.. He was hit with the product. He was able to get it capped. He estimates in less than 1 minutes and estimates less than 20 gallons spilled.     He went into the Safety Shower. EMS was called. His skin was getting a little red so the EMS suggested he go to the ER to be checked out. He states that he was at the ER for a number of hours and they observed him. He had no ill effects and was discharged.

column168: a single vehicle accident (CTMV vs POLE) resulted in the release of approximately 15 gallons of a UN1203 Gasoline from the hard piping lines of the CTMV to area of asphalt parking lot. No drains, soils or waterways were reported to have been impacted. An environmental contractor was dispatched and performed the clean up operations. Granular absorbents, pads and boom were used to contain and clean the release. All wastes were collected, containerized and will be taken for profiling and disposal.

On August 04, 2017 during unloading operations, terminal personnel discovered (1) 15-gallon poly drum containing UN2920 Alkylamine Ethoxylate "Platinum Seal", that was punctured during a load shift. Approximately 10-gallons released to the concrete dock floor when they were offloading. No waterways, soils, or drains were reported to have been impacted. The terminal personnel cleaned and contained the release by utilizing granular absorbents. The damaged drum and impacted debris was overpacked into a (1) 95-gallon poly drum which was staged in OS&D.

(1) 30 Gal Poly Drum of NA1760 Lava Foam White Cleaning Compounds damaged prior to arriving at the terminal from the shipper, resulting in the release of approximately 2 gallons of material to the trailer floor. An environmental contractor was dispatched and over packed the damaged drum and staged it on site pending the shipper's disposition. A commercial branded neutralizer was applied the impacted area and solidified with absorbents. All waste was containerized and left on site for the client to manage

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT OVER BY A CLERK FROM OVERGOODS. THE PACKAGE WAS OPEN AND LEAKING. THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INSIDE A LINED SPILL TRAY BY A CERTIFIED DMP RESPONDER. THE PACKAGE WAS INSPECTED BY SAME RESPONDER. RESPONDER DISCOVERED THAT LEAKING PACKAGE WAS A HAZMAT. THE PACKAGE GAVE NO INDICATION OF ANY HAZARDOUS MERCHANDISE. RESPONDER CALLED HAZMAT HELPDESK. MERCHANDISE WAS AN UNDECLARED HAZMAT. PICTURES OF PACKAGE AND MERCHANDISE WERE TAKEN BY RESPONDER AND SENT TO ADG COMPLIANCE. PACKAGE WILL BE HELD FOR FURTHER INSPECTION.

CARTON MARKED "CO2 CARTRIDGE". "CONTENTS: TWO 74G CARTRIDGES" - HAZMAT TRIGGER TERMS. SHIPMENT OPENED FOR INSPECTION REVEALING 2 GAS CYLINDERS. PRODUCT LABEL STATES: "...PER 49CFR 173.306 LIMITED QUANTITY LESS THAN 115 ML CAPACITY." HAZMAT HELPDESK CALLED - TREAT AS UNDECLARED (TRIGGER TERMS DO NOT QUALIFY AS PROPER SHIPPING NAME MARKINGS PER RULING FROM HMA AND COMPLIANCE). HOLD PENDING REGULATORY INVESTIGATION. REFERENCE #333362.  OTHER PKG TRACKING #'S 0390989244, 0397166834,   0398353451.

column26: 10720 WEST SAM HOUSTON PKWY N SUITE 250
column168: AT 0844 ON 8/6/17, WCTS STEADY CRANE DRIVER LARRY CAMEZ LOADED 1X20’ TANK CONTAINER TO STOW POSITION 131582. THIS CONTAINER WAS NOT SCHEDULED FOR BAY 13 AND WAS THEREFORE LOADED ERRONEOUSLY. AT 0846, SUBJECT CONTAINER TQMU1855400, ORIGINALLY PRESTOWED FOR 131582, WAS INCORRECTLY LOADED TO 131584. AFTER LOADING TWO ADDITIONAL CONTAINERS TO BAY 13 ON DECK FOR THE STOWAGE ERROR WAS APPARENTLY DISCOVERED. AT 0855 TQMU1855400 WAS TAKEN OFF OF THE VESSEL AND BROUGHT BACK TO THE DOCK IN ORDER TO REMOVE THE TWISTLOCKS FROM THE BOTTOM CORNER CASTINGS. WITHOUT EVER DISENGAGING FROM THE CONTAINER, THE CRANE OPERATOR RETURNED TQMU1855400 TO THE VESSEL. SINCE THE INTENDED STOW POSITION WAS STILL OCCUPIED BY THE INCORRECT CONTAINER, MR. CAMEZ ELECTED TO PLACE TQMU1855400 IN A TEMPORARY POSITION ON THE HATCH COVER SO THAT HE COULD REMOVE THE INCORRECTLY STOWED CONTAINER. UNFORTUNATELY, THE TEMPORARY POSITION THAT WAS CHOSE WAS ALREADY SET UP TO RECEIVE 40’ CONTAINERS WHICH MEANT THAT THE DECK CONES THAT WERE ALREADY IN PLACE WERE SITUATED APPROXIMATELY 18” AFT FROM THE FRONT OF THE CONTAINER. MR. CAMEZ LOWERED THE CONTAINER DIRECTLY ATOP THE OFFSHORE DECK CONE THAT WAS LOCATED IN 140482 WHICH IN TURN PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF TQMU1855400. THE LEAKAGE WAS NOT IMMEDIATELY NOTICEABLE TO ANYONE WHILE THE CONTAINER REMAINED IN THIS POSITION WITH THE CONE LODGED IN THE RUPTURE. AFTER DISCHARGING THE INCORRECTLY STOWED CONTAINER, MR. CAMEZ THEN RE-ENGAGED TQMU1855400 TO FINALLY LOAD IT INTO THE CORRECT POSITION. ONCE THE CONTAINER WAS CLEAR OF THE DECK CONE, THE LIQUID CARGO BEGAN TO FLOW FROM THE DAMAGED TANK. WHILE LEAKING, TQMU1855400 WAS ULTIMATELY RE-HANDLED TO THE ORIGINAL PLANNED STOW LOCATION OF 130582. PRODUCT CONTINUED TO FLOW FROM THIS CONTAINER FROM 0900 UNTIL 1203 WHEN THE CONTAINER WAS FINALLY DISCHARGED TO THE DOCK AND CONTROL OF THE RELEASE WAS ESTABLISHED. SEE FOLLOWING PAGES FOR DIAGRAM AND PHOTOS.   EMERGENCY RESPONSE  THE INCIDENT WAS DISCOVERED IMMEDIATELY (0902) BY MR. CAMEZ WHO NOTIFIED ILWU FOREMAN ED MONDOR BY RADIO. MR. MONDOR IMMEDIATELY INFORMED WCTS VESSEL SUPERINTENDENT ERIC WHEELER. MR. MONDOR ALSO INFORMED THE VESSEL PERSONNEL THAT WERE IN THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY OF THE INCIDENT. DUE TO THE RAPID FLOW OF THE LEAK IT WAS DECIDED TO ORDER THE IMMEDIATE EVACUATION OF ALL LONGSHORE PERSONNEL FROM THE AREA. ERIC WHEELER INITIATED NOTIFICATION TO WCTS MANAGEMENT.   AT 0916 WCTS MANAGER DONNEGAN LOBO CONTACTED ITS FSO GREG STUHR. IT WAS JOINTLY AGREED THAT WCTS WOULD INSTRUCT ITS SECURITY TO CALL 911 (CALL PLACED AT 0925) TO REQUEST AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE FROM LBFD FOR BOTH MEDICAL AND HAZMAT EMERGENCIES. SECURITY DIRECTED LBFD FIRST RES-PONDERS TO BERTH 232 AND THE MO PATIO WHERE 10 LONGSHOREMEN WERE COMPLAINING OF DISCOMFORT DUE TO EXPOSURE TO CHEMICAL FUMES.   GREG STUHR PLACED AN ORDER (AT 0923) FOR EMERGENCY CLEANUP RESPONSE WITH PATRIOT ENVIRONMENTAL. LBFD TOOK CONTROL AS INCIDENT COMMANDER AT THE INCIDENT SITE AT 0934. PATRIOT ASSETS BEGAN
column169: THIS INCIDENT PROVIDED A CLEAR EXAMPLE OF THE NEED FOR HEIGHTENED AWARENESS OF THE INHERENT AND ADDITIONAL RISKS INVOLVED WITH HANDLING BULK LIQUIDS IN PORTABLE TANKS. ITS INTENDS TO USE THIS INCIDENT AS A TRAINING TOOL TO RAISE AWARENESS AMONG STEADY FOREMEN, CRANE OPERATORS AND CLERKS.

column168: On August 25, 2017 at 0253 hours, personnel at CSXT discovered UTLX 130576, a residue UN1789, Hydrochloric Acid tank car to have released product from the protective housing area of the car. The car was isolated and the Shipper, PVS Chemicals, Inc. was notified via CHEMTREC, report 2017-08-25-00016. A CSX Emergency Response contractor, Sunpro was dispatched to the scene. Upon inspection, it was determined the liquid line had not been closed after being off loaded.  Sunpro closed and secured the valve, and cleaned up the release.

Driver hooked up a "capped" unloading hose to trailer API head connection.  Once connected the driver opened the API head, charging the unloading hose.  Driver went to connect the "charged" unloading hose and when doing this removed the cap from the hose causing a 30 gallon spill of diesel fuel onto a concrete & asphalt parking lot.  Driver immediately closed API head valve stopping the source of the spill. Driver then deployed spill kit, keeping the product contained to the parking lot.  Environmental contractor was dispatched to the scene for remediation of the spill.
column169: Driver was sent back through three days of retraining of proper unloading procedures.

column168: VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING N/B ON US 49. VEHICLE FAILED TO KEEP PROPER LANE AND RAN OFF RIGHT-SIDE OF ROADWAY. VEHICLE STRUCK A DRAINAGE DITCH AND OVERTURNED. DRIVER OF VEHICLE WAS NOT WEARING SEAT BELT AND WAS EJECTED FROM VEHICLE CAUSING DEATH. AFTER THE ACCIDENT, THE INTERNAL VALVES ON THE CARGO TANK PERFORMED AS DESIGNED BUT SMALL AMOUNTS OF PROPANE SEEPED OUT OF THE PIPING ON THE VEHICLE.
column169: DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE HAD BEEN TRAINED AND HAD PREVIOUS EXPERIENCE DRIVING CMV’S THE ACCIDENT MAY HAVE OCCURRED DUE TO UNFORESEEABLE MEDICAL ISSUES. AS SUCH, NO SPECIFIC CHANGE COULD OR WOULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS ACCIDENT OR FUTURE ACCIDENTS BASED ON SIMILAR UNFORESEEABLE ISSUES.

column162: SVP, TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE AND HEALTH & SAFETY
column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc was en route from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility.  During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at a 10 day transfer facility for the purpose of consolidating less than truck load quantities on a single transport vehicle for continued transportation. During the transport operation, the driver conducted a routine load check and at that time he noted a small amount of product had escaped the package.  The driver contacted his manager.  Facility personnel assembled a response team who proceeded to place the compromised  container into a suitable salvage drum. In addition, all clean-up debris was collected and placed into the salvage drum. Once complete, the container was secured and was placed onto the trailer for continued transportation.  At the time of over-packing, it was learned the gasket was twisted.  This was not something the driver would have been able to see during the inspection phase.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of damage or leaking was observed. Drivers will continue to inspect each container during all  stages of transport and will take all appropriate actions should a container show evidence of reduced structural integrity. IN addition, the shipper has been advised of the situation and has been asked to provide their employees retraining regarding proper closure of containers and drums to include inspecting and properly placing gaskets.

column168: On August 22, 2017,  XPO Logistics NBM reported .5-gallons of UN1993, Flammable Liquid, n.o.s., 3, PGII, trade name HANDI-I-SAN, released from (1) 1-gallon poly jug impacting the concrete dock floor. The jugs were reportedly punctured by a forklift blade. The release was contained to the dock floor. No soils, waterways, or drains were impacted by the release.  XPO Logistics terminal personnel used granular absorbents to clean the release prior to contacting ERTS. The punctured jug and impacted absorbents were containerized into (1) 10-gallon steel drum and placed into OS&D.

column168: This incident pertains to a release of a UN3267 Corrosive liquid, basic, organic, n.o.s. "2-diethylamino ethanol" 8, PGII. There was (1) - 275 poly tote damaged and approximately 15 gallons of this material released. This release was caused by a puncture from a sharp object during transit. This release impacted a portion of the trailer and the asphalt parking lot below the trailer. No soils, drains, or waterways were impacted by this release. A certified environmental contractor was dispatched and this release was cleaned up in accordance with local, state, and federal location.

At 1215 ERTS received a call from Carlton Sabo of United Vision Logistics (Terminal #499) to report a spill. It was reported at 1145 ET, driver Hyren Mitchell of truck #39099  was driving on Highway 61 North bound (no Mile Marker given) when he was cut off, causing the trailer to jerk and (1) 275 Gal Poly tote of UN3264 "PL-8020"  Corrosive liquid, acidic, inorganic, n.o.s. fell off the trailer impacting the ground releasing approximately 275 Gallons of corrosive liquid to asphalt and soil of the area. E3 Environmental was dispatched for the response and arrived on site at approximately  1515 ET on 8/31 with MSDEQ representative to assess the site. Areas appeared to be affected areas were pH'd with litmus paper and discovered to be neutralized with heavy rain. The impact to soil could not be determined based on the heavy rain fall. Per MSDEQ representative Caleb Covington no remediation necessary due to spill impacting rural area, public exposure being limited, and no visual evidence remaining.     Damaged tote was cut up and removed from site by E3 Environmental for disposal.     59646

column168: On 8/25/2017 at 1440 personnel in the CSXT South Philadelphia Yard discovered GATX 14242, a loaded tank car of Hydrogen Peroxide Aqueous Solutions, leaking from the top of the tank car. The car was isolated and Solvay Chemicals Inc. and Transflo, were notified via Chemtrec report #2017082500188. Hepaco, CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found a blown out rupture disk. Contractor personnel replaced the disk with the spare disk located in the extra disk holder. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.
WHILE UNLOADING THE TRAILER, ONE BOX WAS FOUND CRUSHED AND LEAKING. THE RELEASE WAS PROPERLY MANAGED, THE DAMAGED FREIGHT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND HELD PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.
column169: ALWAYS BLOCK AND BRACE FREIGHT TO PREVENT MOVEMENT.

column168: On 08/18/2017, at 1000 hours, a Hazardous Materials Federal Railroad Administration Inspector in the CSXT Collinwood Yard discovered GATX 56391, a loaded tank car of Environmentally Hazardous Substance, Liquid, n.o.s., leaking from manway nozzle. The car was isolated and the National Response Center and Lubrizol Corporation (shipper) were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report # 2017-0818-00120). SUNPRO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the manway nozzle gasket with excessive wear resulting in a release of product. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Mr. Joseph Eskra, phone 440-364-9372. Contractor personnel replaced the gasket in kind and cleaned all material on the sides of the car. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required.    Cause Code: 209  NARRI:5(5+1+5) x (2+0) = 110
column169: Recommend shipper review with loading personnel the inspection of nozzle gaskets prior to certifying the securement of any tank car for transportation.    (NAR:209)

column162: DIRECTOR, HAZ MAT FIELD OPS + ER
column168: On 8/25/17 received notification from Hub personnel at the BNSF Los Angeles IMF (MP145), that unit JBHU 297693 was leaking from under the container floor, reported by the assigned driver prior to outgate. Shipment was billed as Hazardous Material with various HazMat commodities, in the interest of safety, the unit was placed on hold from outgating and was moved to the containment pit area pending interior inspection of the cargo. LA County Fire Dept.  Health HazMat Team responded to the spill. The leaking substance was tested by United Pumping Services, the unknown liquid tested positive for acidic hazardous materials. Interior inspection revealed mixfreight varying in sizes and weight, stowed throughout the whole container. Responders offloaded and transferred freight to discover eight 55 gallon drums on pallets labeled as ORTHOPERIODIC ACID (UN3093) Hazardous Corrosive, that had been crushed due to a second and third layer of palletized freight being stacked on top. The damage to the drums resulted in product spilling from the holes on the sides, losing approximately 100 gallons of product. Responders were able to recover approximately 10  15 gallons of product that spilled on the container floor and on the ground, the damaged drums were placed in over pack drums and properly labeled. Contaminated freight was remediated and loaded back into the original trailer, the remaining freight had to be split and loaded into good order empty unit JBHU 309013. Both units were released for outgate at the drivers  discretion.
column169: The originating terminal should ensure that proper loading procedures are followed to prevent excessive weight from being placed on lower containers.

column60: Burst or Ruptured; Failed to Operate
column62: Defective Component or Device; Inadequate Maintenance
column168: Driver arrived at facility and prepped the cargo tank to be unloaded.  The facility personnel hooked up their hose to tank, and, using an industrial sized pump, began pumping the product out of the cargo tank into their storage.  While the product was being unloaded, our driver heard a loud "cracking noise", and looked over to see the cargo tank shell collapsing.  Immediately, acid began to pour from the tank onto the dirt ground at the facility.  It is unknown how long the acid spilled from the trailer, but, the trailer was estimated at half full at the time of failure and near empty after all product drained from tank.  It is believed that about 2500 gallons of Hydrochloric Acid spilled.  The local fire department was contacted, and once it appeared safe, facility personnel began to try to neutralize the acid using chemicals that they had on-hand.  Once product was neutralized and the site deemed "safe", the facility and shipper arranged for remediation from an environmental service of their choice.  The following day, the driver was allowed to unhook from the trailer and exit the facility in his tractor.  The cargo tank was left on-site for further investigation by safety personnel and insurance adjusters.
column169: Upon investigation, it is our belief that the driver properly prepped the cargo tank for offload.  It is believed that either the vent valve on the trailer failed or that the 2 inch vent line could not "keep up" with the pump used to offload.  The investigation, thus far, is not complete.  Therefore, we're unable to determine the root cause of the accident.  Once the cause is determined, we will be better able to understand what changes can/should be made.

column168: AT 1:13 ON 8/10/2017 IT WAS REPORTED THAT THERE IS A STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE EMPTY TANK CAR DBUX 340117 (LAST CONTAINED LPG) IN THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAYS PORT ARTHUR YARD. THE ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DISPATCHED A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND SECURE THE CAR.     USING A LEAK DETECTION SOLUTION, THE CONTRACTOR FOUND BOTH THE B END LIQUID VALVE AND B END LIQUID VALVE PLUG LOOSE AND THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE THREADS OF THE PLUG. BOTH THE PLUG AND VALVE WERE TIGHTENED TOOL TIGHT, STOPPING THE LEAK. ALL OTHER CLOSURES ON THE CAR WERE CHECKED AND FOUND TO BE TIGHT.    FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTIFY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A “BULK” SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSES(S) OF RELEASE AND THEN TO FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.  (NAR: 119)
column198: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY COMPANY

column168: AIRGAS DELIVERY DRIVER MADE A DELIVERY TO THE CUSTOMER TANK. ONCE COMPLETE HE WAS SHUTTING ALL VALVES + BLEEDING REMAINING RESIDUE PRODUCT INTO A BUCKET OF WATER. WHILE BLEEDING OFF THE DRIVER HEARD A POP, SAW A WHITE CLOUD, GRABBED HIS RESPIRATOR, SHUT THE CUSTOMERS FACILITY DOOR + EVACUATED PEOPLE FROM NEARBY THE TANK. OUR FIELD SERVICE TECHNICIAN ARRIVED ONSITE + FOUND A LOOSE ACME FITTING. HE TIGHTENED THE FITTING + STOPPED THE LEAK. HE ALSO FOUND A FAILED VALVE THAT CAUSED THE LEAK. THE FAULTY VALVE WAS ON THE HOSE END + ALL VALVES ON THE TRUCK END HELD. SO THEY BLEW THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE HOSE INTO A WATER DRUM + REPLACED THE BROKEN VALVE ONSITE. UPON REMOVAL OF THE VALVE IT WAS FOUND THE INTERNAL COMPONENTS ARE WHAT FAILED.
column169: REPLACED DELIVERY VALVE  REPLACED ALL OTHER ACME FITTINGS IN CASE THERE WAS DAMAGE.   WE’RE CURRENTLY WORKING W/ THE VALVE MANUFACTURE TO DETERMINE WHAT CAUSED THE INTERNAL COMPONENTS TO FAIL.

column168: A BOX TRUCK CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY FOR AN OFFLOAD TO TRANSFER AND CONSOLIDATE ITS WASTE ONTO A VAN TRAILER TO ITS INTENDED WASTE DISPOSAL FACILITY. UPON ENTERING THE VEHICLE’S CARGO AREA, THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT HE HAD A RELEASE WHILE IN TRANSIT. HE NOTIFIED HIS MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY, AND A RESPONSE CREW WAS NOTIFIED. THE RESPONSE CREW DONNED THE APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, ENTERED THE TRUCK, AND DISCOVERED THAT THE CENTER CAP ON A TOTE HAD COME OFF, ALLOWING A RELEASE WHICH WAS CONTAINED IN THE VEHICLE BOX; NO SOIL OR WATERWAYS WERE IMPACTED. THE TOTE WAS FOUND TO HAVE BEEN OVERFILLED; THE LACK OF APPROPRIATE HEAD-SPACE CAUSED AN EXCESS PRESSURE BUILD UP GIVEN THE WARM WEATHER CONDITIONS. SOME WASTE WAS TRANSFERRED OUT OF THE TOTE TO ALLOW MORE HEAD-SPACE; THAT TRANSFERRED WASTE WAS PACKAGED IN THE CORRECT UN SPECIFICATION CONTAINER FOR LATER DISPOSAL. THE BOX TRUCK FLOOR WAS CLEANED WITH A CLEANING COMPOUND AND RETURN FOR SERVICE; THE WASTE GENERATED FROM THE CLEAN UP WAS PLACED IN THE CORRECT UN SPECIFICATION CONTAINER FOR LATER DISPOSAL.   REPORTED TO NJ DEP 8/5/17 TO OPERATOR 75, REPORT NUMBER 17-0805-1930-14
column169: THE HHW (HAZARDOUS HOUSEHOLD WASTE) CREW RESPONSIBLE FOR THE FILLING OF THIS TOTE, AND THE DRIVER WHO TRANSPORTED THIS TOTE WERE ALL GIVEN RETRAINING ON CORRECT TOTE FILLING AND INSPECTION PROCEDURES. IN ADDITION, THIS INCIDENT WAS DISCUSSED WITH ALL BRANCH HHW CREW AND DRIVERS TO HELP PREVENT A RECURRENCE.

column168: ON AUGUST 17, 2017 AT 1720 AND UNRECOGNIZABLE ODOR WAS REPORTED IN THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN SHREVEPORT YARD. KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT DEPLOYED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE. AFTER WALKING THE YARD, GATX 23502 WAS FOUND WITH RESIDUE (CREOSOTE) ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE CAR EMANATING FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.     ROOT CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DETERMINED TO BE A HARD COUPLING RESULTING IN THE SPRING LOADED RECLOSEABLE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) TO RELEASE 0.06 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ONTO THE OUTSIDE OF THE CAR. SUBSEQUENT PRESSURE TESTING OF GATX 23502 SHOWED THAT THE PRD WAS NOT DEFECTIVE.     FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A “BULK’ SHIPMENT, AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE, DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.  (NAR: 700)

column168: DRIVER WAS AT REST AREA OVERNIGHT. WHEN HE WOKE UP IN THE MORNING, HE NOTICED THAT LIQUID HAD LEAKED OUT OF THE FRONT TRAILER. ONCE NOTICED HE IMMEDIATELY LAID DOWN ABSORBENTS TO CONTAIN SPILLED MATERIAL.    A CLEANUP CREW IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED. THE DRUM HAD TIPPED OVER AND THE BUNG ON THE DRUM WAS LOOSE. ACID WAS DRIPPING OUT OF LOOSE BUNG.     CREW TIGHTENED LEAKING BUNG AND INSPECTED DRUM TO ENSURE IT WAS STILL DOT SHIPPABLE. TOTAL SHIPMENT WAS RE-SECURED, BALANCED, AND SHIPPED ONCE AREA WAS CLEANED AND DECONTAMINATED.
column169: AN INCIDENT REVIEW MEETING WAS HELD TO REVIEW THE INCIDENT. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT RETRAINING NEEDED TO OCCUR IN ORDER TO ENSURE THAT LOADS ARE PROPERLY INSPECTED PRIOR TO SHIPMENT. THIS INCLUDES THE INSPECTION OF EVERY CONTAINER TO ENSURE THEY ARE DOT SHIPPABLE AND ENSURING THAT LOADS ARE PROPERLY BALANCES, BLOCKED AND BRACED IN ORDER TO PREVENT ANY TYPE OF MOVEMENT DURING TRANSPORTATION.

column168: On August 31, 2017, at 1045 hours, Mechanical Foreman at the CSXT Dewitt Yard, Easy Syracuse, New York reported that an FRA Hazardous Material Inspector took exception to TILX 160826, a loaded tank car of UN1824, sodium hydroxide solution. Reportedly there was product around and the manway with two (2) swing securement bolts loose and hanging down. The tank car was isolated and the shipper, Axiall Corp., was notified via Chemtrec, report #2017-08-31-00124. Hepaco, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Dewitt Yard to properly secure and decontaminate the tank car. Hepaco found that two securement swing bolts on the manway were in fact loose and the release was from that condition. Additionally, Hepaco found both the liquid and vapor line secondary securement plugs less than tool tight. Hepaco secured the tank car for continuance in transportation. The shipper representative, Matt Bond, 304-266-8287 was notified of the situation found.     NARRI: 5x(5+7+0)x(2+0) = 120  Cause code:200

column168: WHILE INSPECTING AN OUTBOUND VAN TRAILER LOAD INTENDED FOR THE FINAL DISPOSAL FACILITY, THE DRIVER DISCOVERED MATERIAL RELEASED ONTO THE VAN FLOOR. FACILITY PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED. CORDONED OFF THE AREA AND PLACED ABSORBENTS PADS UNDER THE TRAILER TO PREVENT THE POSSIBILITY OF MATERIAL LEAKING ON THE GROUND. A FIELD SERVICE RESPONSE TEAM WAS SUMMONED TO ASSES THE SITUATION. DONNED IN THE APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, THE RESPONSE CREW DISCOVERED A 5 G POLYETHYLENE PAIL HAD TIPPED OVER AND WAS LEAKING FORM ITS LD. THE RELEASE IMPACTED ONLY THE VAN FLOOR, NO GROUND SOIL OR WATER WERE AFFECTED. UPON CLOSER SCRUTINY IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE 5 G PAIL THOUGH THE MATERIALS ORIGINAL COMMODITY SHIPPING CONTAINER WAS NOT A UN SPECIFICATION PACKAGE. THIS LEAKING PAIL AND TWO OTHER IDENTICAL NON LEAKING PAILS WERE OVER PACKED INTO SUITABLE UN RATED SALVAGE DRUM , THESE CONTINUED ONTO THE INTENDED DISPOSAL DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.   THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS THOROUGHLY CLEANED AND THE WASTE GENERATED FROM THIS CLEANUP WAS PLACED INTO THE APPROPRIATE WASTE STREAM FRO INTER DISPOSAL. THIS RELEASE FELL BELOW THE REPORTING THRESHOLD FOR THE STATE OF OHIO
column169: THE ORIGINAL DRIVER WHO ACCEPTED THESE PACKAGES INTO TRANSIT, ALONG WITH THE MATERIAL HANDLER WHO SECURED THESE PAILS ON THE ORIGINAL CONSOLIDATED LOAD, WERE TRAINED IN PACKAGE INSPECTION AND CONTAINER SPECIFICATION. THEY WERE ALSO GIVE ADDITIONAL LOAD SECUREMENT AND INSPECTION INSTRUCTION. THE GENERATOR WAS COUNSELED ON THE NECESSITY FOR ALL WASTE STREAMS TO PROPERLY PACKAGED IN UN SPECIFICATION CONTAINERS AND THE POSSIBILITY THAT A COMMODITY BECOMING A WASTE MIGHT CHANGE THE PACKAGING REQUIREMENTS.

column168: During the unloading operation at the ExxonMobil Baytown Refinery, a leak occurred from the carrier's hose and resulted in a 30 gallon spill.  The unloading operation was stopped immediately.  The material that spilled on the pavement was soaked up with sand/gravel, placed in a container and stored before it was properly disposed of. Some of the material also contacted the truck driver.  The driver was immediately taken to a safety shower and rinsed, then taken to a local medical facility for evaluation.  There was no treatment given and the driver was released with no restrictions.  During the course of the investigation, it was determined that the truck driver inadvertently pulled a hose off of his truck that was expired.  Further inspection of the hose indicated excessive wear at the "bend" area which most likely contributed to the failure.
column169: The carrier company (L & B Transport) provided a warning to the driver related to proper pre-use inspection of unloading hoses.  L & B Transport is conducting a thorough review of all hoses to be sure they are within their expiration dates.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Flight 1186 from Tampa arrived into Chicago at 1613, parking on gate H8.  The aircraft number was NC#3CG.  Upon arrival, the forward cargo compartment was opened and it was noticed that there had been a spill of a white liquid that had already dried.  After investigating, we determined that the passenger's bag contained 4 bottles of cleaner with bleach.  Of the 4 bottles of cleaner, one had opened and completely emptied its contents, totaling 32 fluid ounces.  The tile cleaner flowed from approximately 6 feet left of the forward cargo door to 2 feet to the right of the forward cargo door and it dried in place leaving a white residue on the cargo compartment floor.  As this was a spill of known origin we completed the offload and called aircraft maintenance to inspect the Cargo compartment to ensure the aircraft was safe to continue to travel. The captain placed an item in the logbook and aircraft maintenance took the aircraft out of service to be able to pull the floorboards and complete a thorough inspection. The on the bag in question was #5001955519, tagged for passenger Padmanabharao Uppalapatisrikrishna.  The passenger was travelling from Tampa to O'Hare and then connecting to British Airways with a final destination of Hyderabad, India.
column169: In this case, the passenger checked his bag in Tampa.  He did not declare the dangerous goods in his bag, but he may have not known.  American Airlines does train their people in dangerous goods and our ticket counter folks ask the question if there are any hazardous materials inside the bags being checked.  This bag was screened by the TSA in Tampa and the TSA missed the 4 (32-oz) containers of cleaner with bleach.  Perhaps they were unaware that the cleaner was dangerous goods.  The recommendation would be to ensure that all personnel are properly trained on dangerous goods in baggage.  When in doubt the TSA should pull the item out of the bag.

column168: ON 8/21/2017 AT APPROXIMATELY 14:14, THE GATX 10959 WAS REPORTED BY CALUMET REFINING PERSONNEL TO HAVE RESIDUE ON THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR AND REPORTED TO THE BNSF GREAT FALLS TRAIN-MASTER. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED ON CALUMET’S PROPERTY AND BNSF RESPONDED WITH A CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT, REPAIR AND CLEAN THE CAR. THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE RUPTURE DISK HAD BLOWN AND SODIUM HYDROXIDE HAD RELEASED FROM THE CAR THROUGH THE VENT OPENING. THERE WAS NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT AND ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ISOLATED TO THE CAR BODY. THE RUPTURE DISK WAS REPLACED AND THE RESIDUE ON THE CAR NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED.
column169: WHILE ITS UNKNOWN AS TO THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE RELEASE. THE SHIPPER SHOULD ENSURE THAT RUPTURE DISKS ARE IN GOOD CONDITION WHEN PERFORMING POST LOAD INSPECTIONS PRIOR TO RELEASE OF THE PACKAGE. ADDITIONALLY, LOCAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS SHOULD ENSURE THAT CARS ARE NOT COUPLED TOGETHER AT SPEEDS EXCEEDING 4 MPH TO PREVENT POTENTIAL HYDRAULIC SURGES WITHIN THE CARS. THE SHIPPER AND LOCAL OPERATIONS ARE AWARE OF THIS INCIDENT AND ADVISED TO REVIEW PROCEDURES AND PROVIDE BRIEFINGS TO CREWS.

column168: -988-9306 0634(7PCS/1327KG) WAS TENDERED ON 29AUG17 TO ASIANA CARGO W/H AND ACCEPTED AS NON-DANGEROUS GOODS.    -CARGO SCREENER FOUND DANGEROUS GOOD PACKAGES DURING CARGO SCREENING BY X-RAY. (THE DANGEROUS GOODS WERE PACKED WITH “UN SPECIFICATION MARKING” BUT NO SHIPPER’S DECLARATION)    -ASIANA AIRLINES NOTIFIED “UNDECLARED DG” TO INDIRECT AIR CARRIER. (SHIPPER’S AGENT)    -ASIANA AIRLINES TRANSFERRED THE CARGO TO DESTINATION WITH FREIGHTER AFTER REMOVING ALL DANGEROUS GOOD PACKAGES.     THIS EVENT WAS ALSO REPORTED TO FAA. FAA INSTRUCTED ASIANA AIRLINES TO REPORT THIS CASE TO DOT.     THERE IS NO PACKAGE DAMAGE. THIS IS ON “UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS”

column168: On August 31, 2017, a Fluke 451P Ion Chamber Survey Meter (subject to DOT-SP 13187) was transported between the Pacific Northwest National Laboratory Information Science Building-2 and the Battelle Shipping and Receiving Warehouse (BRSW), approximately 0.75 miles on Battelle private roads that were accessible to the public. The staff member offering the instrument intended that other staff at BRSW prepare the instrument for transport to New Mexico.  The staff members offering and transporting the item were not aware that the pressurized gas was present in the instrument or that the special permit applied.  The potential for hazardous material was recognized at BRSW and the shipment stopped.  There was no damage or release.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: WHILE WORKING ON A LARGE SITE REMEDIATION PROJECT, THE DRIVER WAS LOADING THIS WASTE ONTO A VACUUM TANK VEHICLE FROM A DECOMMISSIONED IN-GROUND FUEL TANK; THE DRIVER LOST SUCTION, AND 20 GALLONS OF WASTE GASOLINE WAS RELEASE TO BOTH SOIL AND ASPHALT. NO STORM DRAINS OR BODIES OF WATER WERE IMPACTED. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW WEARING THE CORRECT PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT WAS DISPATCHED, AND BEGAN THE PROCESS OF CLEANING AND RE-MEDIATING THE SITE. THIS PROCESS IS STILL GOING WITH GUIDANCE FROM THE STATE OF NEW HAMPSHIRE. IT'S FULL COMPLETION HAS BEEN COMPLICATED BY SOIL SAMPLE ANALYSIS LAG AND THE DIFFICULTY IN DIFFERENTIATING NEW RELEASE IMPACTED SOIL FROM SOIL IMPACTED PREVIOUSLY THAT IS BEING RE-MEDIATED AS PART OF A LARGER PROJECT. DURING AN INCIDENT INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DRIVER WAS UNFAMILIAR WITH THIS PARTICULAR PIECE OF EQUIPMENT AND PUT THE SUCTION/PRESSURE LEVER IN THE WRONG POSITION. IT WAS ALSO DETERMINED THAT THE LEVER IN QUESTION WAS NOT ADEQUATELY MARKED.  THIS WAS REPORTED TO THE STATE OF NEW HAMPSHIRE DES ON 8/23/17 TO GARDNER WARR.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: AFTER EXITING THE VEHICLE, HAVING ARRIVED AT A INTENDED WASTE TRANSFER/TREATMENT DESTINATION. THE DRIVER NOTICED HIS VAN TRAILER WAS LEAKING TO ASPHALT. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY MOVED THE AFFECTED TRAILER INTO A FACILITY CONTAINMENT AREA, AND NOTIFIED THE FACILITY. FACILITY PERSONNEL WEARING THE APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE GEAR, CORDONED OFF THE AREA, AND DEPLOYED ABSORBENT AND BOOM TO PREVENT THE RELEASE FROM SPREADING FURTHER. THE RELEASE WAS LIMITED TO ASPHALT, CONCRETE AND A CONTAINMENT AREA. A FULL EMERGENCY FIELD SERVICE RESPONSE CREW WAS DISPATCHED TO RESPOND TO THIS RELEASE. WHEN THEY ARRIVED EQUIPPED WITH THE CORRECT PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, THEY ENTERED THE TRAILER, AND DETERMINED THAT AN IBC TOTE HAS BEEN PUNCTURED BY A PIECE OF WOOD PALLET. THE FIELD SERVICE RESPONSE CREW CLEANED UP THE ASPHALT AND CONCRETE IMPACTED AND FULLY CLEANED THE INSIDE OF THE AFFECTED TRAILER. THE WASTE LEFT REMAINING IN THE PUNCTURED IBC WAS TRANSFERRED TO A UN SPECIFICATION PACKAGE. AND THE WASTE GENERATED DURING THE CLEANUP PLACED IN AN APPROPRIATE WASTE STREAM FOR LATER DISPOSAL. DURING AN INCIDENT INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LOAD HAD INSUFFICIENT LOAD SECUREMENT, WHICH ALLOWED THIS TOTE AND SOME PALLETS USED AS DUNNAGE TO SHIFT SUBSTANTIALLY DURING AN HARSH CORNERING MANEUVER/HARD BRAKING THAT OCCURRED WHILE THE DRIVE WAS ENTERING THIS FACILITY. TI WAS ALSO DETERMINED THAT THE PLACEMENT OF THIS TOTE AND THE DUNNAGE USE TO PREVENT MOVEMENT WAS INADEQUATE AND POORLY POSITIONED.   THIS WAS REPORTED TO RON BONNER FROM OHIO EPA AT 20:02 EST 08/23/2017 HE HAD LARRY ANTONELLI REACH OUT TO MEAN AT 20:05EST. HE WAS SATISFIED WITH OUR RESPONSE. THIS WAS ALSO REPORTED TO THE CUYAHOGA COUNTY LEPC (216-771-1365) TO OFFICER GRAHAM BADGE #011 AT 20:16 EST ON 08/23/2017. SHE WAS SATISFIED WITH OUR RESPONSE. THIS WAS ALSO REPORTED OT THE CLEVELAND FD TO NICK PASTORIK LT KELLY AT 20:15 EST 08/23/2017. I WAS CALLED BACK AT 20:40 BY LT KELLY, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DIVISION. HE WAS SATISFIED WHIT OUR RESPONSE. column169: THE DRIVER OF THIS LOAD WAS ISSUED A FORMAL DISCIPLINARY WARNING. BOTH THE DRIVER OF THIS LOAD, AND ALL THE FACILITY MATERIAL HANDLERS INVOLVED IN THE LOADING OF THIS TRAILER, WHERE GIVEN RETRAINING ON LOAD SECUREMENT, WITH AN EMPHASIS ON SECURING AT INTERVALS EACH LOAD IN THE REAR AND LATERAL DIRECTIONS TO AT LEAST 50% OF THE LOAD WEIGHT WITH WORKING LOAD LIMIT RATED DEVICES, AND ON ELIMINATING VOID SPACES THE COULD ALLOW FOR LOAD SHIFT.THE DRIVER WAS ALSO GIVEN ADDITIONAL ZURICH DEFENSIVE DRIVING TRAINING

column168: DRIVER WAS MAKING A 90 DEGREE TURN ONTO FINLEY STREET FROM BALLSTON AVENUE. MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER SHIFTED CAUSING THE TRAILER TO OVERTURN TAKING THE TRACTOR WITH IT. THERE WAS NO SPILL OF MATERIAL FOR THE TRAILER JUST A SMALL AMOUNT OF ENGINE COOLANT AND HYDRAULIC OIL. THE DEC SPILL RESPONSE DID NOT ISSUE A INCIDENT NUMBER DUE TO THE SMALL AMOUNT . THE SARATOGA CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT CONTAINED THE MATERIAL WITH A FEW SPILL PADS. SLACK CHEMICAL HAD OUR OWN PEOPLE ON SCENE TO ASSIST THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND DID THE TRANSFER OF MATERIAL FROM THE WRECKED TANKER TO A PRODUCT COMPATIBLE TRAILER THAT WAS AT OUR FACILITY LESS THEN 5 MILES AWAY. AFTER THE TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS UPRIGHTED BY MATT'S TOWING SERVICES AND TAKEN TO AN IMPOUND YARD FOR SARATOGA CITY POLICY TO FINISH THEIR INSPECTION. THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE RELEASED BACK TO SLACK CHEMICAL ON 9/15/2017 WITH NO ISSUE FOUND TO CONTRIBUTE TO THE ACCIDENT. IT WAS DETERMINED TO BE DRIVER ERROR.
column169: SLACK CHEMICAL HAS BEEN WORKING WITH OUR INSURANCE CARRIER TO INSTITUTE A DRIVER DEFENSE COURSE TO ENHANCE OUR PROGRAM OF GENERAL SAFETY PRACTICES THAT ARE ALREADY IN PLACE. SLACK CHEMICAL HAS ALSO RECENTLY INSTALLED ELECTRONIC LONG DEVICES THAT HAVE THE CAPACITY OF IDENTIFYING SUCH THINGS AS HARD BRAKING, SPEEDING, AGGRESSIVE MOVES, AND SWERVING. THIS WILL ENHANCE OUR MONITORING OF INDIVIDUALS DRIVERS DRIVING HABITS.

column168: THE TRUCK WAS TRAVELING WEST BOUND ON I26 IN SUMMERVILLE, SC. A TIRE BLEW OUT ON A TRUCK AHEAD OF HIM AND DUMP TRUCK AND A CAR IN BOTH LANES IN FRONT OF HIM HIT THE BRAKES TO MISS THE TIRE IN THE ROAD. THE DRIVER MOVED LEFT AND TRIED TO STOP. HE COULDN’T AND WENT OFF THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROAD TO PREVENT HITTING THE CAR. THE TRUCK HIT THE WET GRASS. THE DRIVER TRIED TO GET BACK ON THE ROAD, BUT THE TRUCK ROLLED ON ITS SIDE. THE DRIVER GOT OUT WITH MINOR INJURIES. FIRE, EMS, AND DOT HAZMAT TEAM WERE CALLED. THERE WAS A SMALL LEAK IN THE CONTAINER. THE IBC’S WERE BENT AND DAMAGED AND MAINLY LEAKING FROM THE VENT CAP. TRUCK WAS UP-RIGHTED, LOAD WAS UNLOADED, AND TRUCK WAS REMOVED.
column169: MANAGEMENT HELD A MEETING WITH THE DRIVER AND DISCUSSED FOLLOWING TOO CLOSE AND A DRIVER WATCHED A DVD ON ROLLOVER PREVENTION. MANAGEMENT DISCUSSED WHAT THINGS COULD BE DONE TO PREVENT THIS ACCIDENT FROM OCCURRING AGAIN.

column168: OUR DRIVER TRAVELING ON HWY 49 TOWARD CHARLOTTE ROUNDING A CURVE WHEN HE NOTED A VEHICLE STOPPED WITH THE LEFT TURN SIGNAL ON. AN ONCOMING VEHICLE PREVENTED THIS CAR FROM MAKING THE TURN. OUR DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO GO AROUND THE CAR ON THE RIGHT SHOULDER. THE WHEELS DROPPED DOWN IN THE SOFT DIRT AT WHICH TIME THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL AND WENT DOWN INTO THE DITCH AND OVERTURNED ON ITS RIGHT SIDE AND THEN BECAUSE OF THE TERRAIN BOUNCED BACK AND TURNED OVER ON ITS LEFT SIDE.
column169: WE ARE PROUD OF THE MANY SAFETY PROCEDURES AND POLICIES WE HAVE. CONSTANTLY MONITOR OUR DRIVERS VIA DASH CAM, SPEED GAGE, ETC. THIS DRIVER HAS A GOOD RECORD WITH US, HOWEVER, IT APPEARS THAT FOR SOME REASON UNKNOWN TO US, HE WAS IN A HURRY AND WAS SPEEDING ON A RURAL TWO LANE HIGHWAY.

column168: THE WRECKER SERVICE WAS LIFTING THE LOADED CARGO TANK AND ONE OF THE CABLES BROKE A DISCHARGE VALVE RESULTING IN THE SPILL.
column169: WRECKER COMPANY TO BETTER TRAIN EMPLOYEES.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING THE CTMV INTO AN AGST IN CONCRETE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. HE MISCALCULATED THE BEGINNING ULLAGE. AS A RESULTS, HE IN CORRECTLY BELIEVED HE HAD ROOM TO UNLOAD INTO THAT STORAGE TANK. THE TANK OVERFILLED, SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF #2 CLEAR DIESEL FUEL INTO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT. THE FUEL SPILL FOR LESS THAN ONE MINUTE AS THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE PUMP. THERE WAS NO FAILURE OF ANY COMPONENT OF EITHER TANK; IT WAS SIMPLY OVERFILLED BY HUMAN ERROR. UPON STOPPING THE FUEL FLOW, THE DRIVER INITIATED RESPONSE AND CHECKED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS REMAINING IN CONTAINMENT. WEST CENTRAL ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANTS WAS CONTACTED TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP. UNDER ITS MANAGEMENT, CONTAMINATED GRAVEL FROM INSIDE CONTAINMENT (ABOVE THE CONCRETE FLOOR) WAS TRANSPORTED TO SOUTHERN IDAHO SOLID WASTE FOR DISPOSAL.

OUR DRIVER APPROACHED A TURN GOING TO FAST FOR ROAD CONDITIONS. AS HE ENTERED THE LEFT HAND TURN HIS VEHICLE LEFT THE ROAD ON THE RIGHT SHOULDER. THE LIP OF THE SHOULDER PULLED THE TANKER VEHICLE FURTHER ONTO THE SHOULDER, THIS CAUSED THE TRUCK TO PULL INTO A DITCH RUNNING PARALLEL TO THE ROAD. THERE WAS A CULVERT PIPE THAT THE TRUCK STRUCK CAUSING IT TO OVER TURN ON ITS LEFT HAND SIDE. THE TRAILER FOLLOWED AND ROLLED ONTO ITS LEFT HAND SIDE, THE FRONT BULKHEAD OF THE TRAILER STRUCK THE ROCK EMBANKMENT, CAUSING THE ALUMINIUM TO RIP OPEN SPILLING THE CONTENTS OF THE FRONT COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER.
column169: REVISIT DRIVER TRAINING AND ENFORCEMENT OF POSTED ROAD SPEEDS.

column168: THE UNLOADING PROCEDURE FOR AHF CARGO TANKS REQUIRES A PRESSURIZATION OF THE TRANSFER HOSES. PROCEDURES IN PLACE REQUIRE PRESSURE TESTING OF ALL HOSES PRIOR TO LOADING AND UNLOADING THE CARGO TANK. DURING THE DELIVERY AND UNLOADING STEP OF THE PROCESS, THE OPERATOR NOTICED A “WISP” FROM THE OFFLOADING HOSE. THE PROCESS WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN. RELEASE AMOUNT WAS DE MINIMIS, LESS THAN 0.5. LB OF VAPOR, AND THE TIME OF RELEASE WAS SECONDS. A TRAINED TECHNICIAN WAS DISPATCHED TO THE LOCATION. HE WAS EQUIPPED WITH PPE, GEAR AND TRANSFER HOSE. USING THE TRANSFER HOSE, THE TECHNICIAN BLED THE CARGO TANK PRESSURE TO LESS THAN 20 PSI, BELOW THE LEVEL PRESCRIBED BY REGULATION. THE HOSES WERE BLED, BLINDED ON EACH END, SECURED IN THE HOSE TROUGH AND THE CARGO TANK RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER WITHOUT OFFLOADING THE PRODUCT. THE FAULTY HOSE WAS SUBSEQUENTLY DECONTAMINATED AND SENT TO A THIRD PARTY FOR INDEPENDENT FAILURE ANALYSIS.
column169: CURRENT PROCEDURE CALL OUT TRANSFER HOSE INSPECTION AND PRESSURE TESTING BEFORE CARGO TANK LOADING AND UNLOADING. ADDITIONALLY, ALL HOSES ARE REPLACED ANNUALLY. WE ARE INVESTIGATING ANY MANUFACTURING DEFECTS OR COMPLAINTS WITH THE HOSE MANUFACTURER. PENDING THIRD PARTY ANALYSIS, WE WILL EVALUATE ANY FURTHER CORRECTIVE ACTIONS OR PROCEDURE MODIFICATIONS.

column168: DURING A ROUTINE TIRE AN LOAD CHECK WHILE STOPPED FOR FUEL, THE DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL RELEASE IN PROGRESS FROM A ROLL-OFF BOX. THE DRIVER DONNED THE APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND TOOK IMMEDIATE STEPS TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE AND PREVENT IT FROM HITTING THE GROUND, DEPLOYING BUCKETS, SPILL PADS, AND ABSORBENTS. THE RELEASE IMPACTED ONLY CONCRETE, AND WAS MOSTLY CAPTURED BY BUCKETS. NO SOIL, WATER, OR STORM DRAINS WERE IMPACTED.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CREW WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE. UTILIZING THE APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, THE CREW DISCOVERED TWO CASUAL FACTORS: FIRST, THE MATERIAL IN THE ROLL-OFF BOX CONTAINED SOME PACKAGING PROHIBITED LIQUIDS; AND THAT SECOND, THE ROLL-OFF BOX HAD DEVELOPED A BREACH DUE TO INTERIOR CORROSION. THE CREW MIXED IN STABILIZING ABSORBENTS TO THE LOAD TO BIND ANY FREE LIQUIDS, AND THEY INSTALLED A PATCH ON THE EXTERIOR OF THE ROLL-OFF TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER LEAKING.  THE ROLL-OFF WAS THEN TAKEN TO A NEARBY FACILITY, WHERE THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED INTO A ROLL-OFF BOX IN PERFECT ORDER. THE ORIGINAL ROLL-OFF BOX WAS THEN SENT TO BE REPAIRED BEFORE IT COULD BE USED AGAIN. THE WASTE, NOW IN A FRESH ROLL-OFF CONTAINER, CONTINUED ON TO IT’S FINAL DISPOSAL DESTINATION WITHOUT INCIDENT.  THE OHIO EPA HOTLINE WAS CONTACTED ON 08/16/17 AT 20:00 AT 800-282-9378; NO REPORT NUMBER WAS ISSUED.
column169: THE JOB-SITE FOREARM AND DRIVER INVOLVED IN THE LOADING AND TRANSPORTATION OF THIS WASTE WERE GIVEN RETRAINING ON LOAD AND CONTAINER INSPECTION, WITH AN EMPHASIS ON VERIFYING THE ABSENCE OF FREE LIQUIDS IN ROLL-OFF CONTAINERS AND CONTAINER INTEGRITY INSPECTION PRIOR TO LOADING.

column168: DURING THE UNLOAD OF A VAN TRAILER AT THIS WATSES INTENDED FINAL DESTINATION, FACILITY PERSONNEL DISCOVERED THAT AN IBC CONTAINER HAD IT’S CAP NOT INSTALLED; THE CAP WAS ON TOP OF THE IBC, ALONG WITH ABOUT 8 OZ OF THE WASTE. NO RELEASE DID NOT IMPACT THE TRAILER, GROUND, SOIL, OR ANY WATER SOURCES, HAVING BEEN LIMITED TO THE TOP OF THE IBC. APPROPRIATELY TRAINED FACILITY PERSONNEL DONNED THE CORRECT PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, INSTALLED THE IBC CAP AS PER THE MANUFACTURER’S SPECIFICATION, AND CLEANED UP THE RELEASED LIQUID. THE WASTE GENERATED BY THE CLEANUP WAS PLACED INTO AN APPROPRIATE BRANCH WASTE STREAM FOR LATER DISPOSAL. THE IBC WAS THEN TRANSFERRED WITHOUT INCIDENT TO THE PART OF THE FACILITY THAT COMPLETES THE FINAL TREATMENT OF THIS WASTE.    THIS RELEASE WAS REPORTED AT 15:30EST 8/21/17 TO THE CT DEEP, REPORT # 2017-04240, OPERATOR 205.
column169: THE GENERATOR WAS INFORMED OF THE INCIDENT, AND THEY PERFORMED A SAFETY STAND DOWN AND RETRAINING OF THE INVOLVED FACILITY EMPLOYEES. THE DRIVER RESPONSIBLE FOR TRANSPORTING THIS IBC WAS GIVEN ADDITIONAL CONTAINER CLOSURE AND INSPECTION TRAINING, WITH AN EMPHASIS ON THE REQUIREMENT TO CHECK ALL IBC CLOSURES, EVEN TALL IBC’S.

column168: August 3, 2017 :17:45 – Advanced Chemical Transportation (ACT) was notified, that an incident involving a container as part of a load being carried by one of the ACT transport vehicles had occurred in Colorado Springs, Colorado.      The truck was headed north on I-25 and the driver noticed smoke escaping the van trailer. The driver stopped the truck, called for emergency help and responded by separating the tractor from the trailer / await responders. Once responder crews arrived, the trailer was opened and a drum had failed due to chemical reaction or fire. The scene was expanded to include closure of I-25 northbound lanes due to the nature of the incident and the lading of the trailer. The southbound traffic was already previously diverted due to construction which created a safe buffer for the public.     The local Fire Department HAZMAT team made entry into the trailer, retrieved the container that was the source of the chemical reaction / fire, and repackaged the container into a salvage drum. The chemical residue that was released onto the trailer floor and asphalt was also repackaged to an appropriate container (salvage drum) for transport. The truck was released by the Fire / EMS crews for transport to safe haven at the ACT yard in Commerce City, Colorado.     The container failed at the bottom 1/3 of the drum, due to heat melting the plastic construction material, resulting in the release of the solid oxidizer material. The material in the package was Household Hazardous Waste (HHW) that is consolidated at a collection facility operated by ACT in Albuquerque, NM.     Interstate 25 was re-opened at approximately 9:00 p.m.
column169: The Household Hazardous Waste (HHW) collection personnel that generate the packages for transport have been re-trained on the packaging procedure to include: 1. Identification of materials and potential incompatibilities, 2. Proper packaging of HHW materials to prevent chemical reaction during storage and shipment.  ACT has also reviewed the procedure to ensure that packaging of HHW oxidizers is appropriate and the procedure has been updated to include inventory and review of container contents prior to storage and shipping.

column168: Action Environmental was notified of a premium gasoline release at 7840 Leonardo Dr., Durham, NC. The release was identified as a failure of a 4” gasoline drop hose (ten {10’} section). A crack/split in the hose caused the release of gas. Based on inventory reconciliation it has been estimated 100 gallons was released to the concrete and asphalt surfaces. The gas entered the storm water drainage system and flowed from box to box. Impact to soil and surface water was not reported. The storm drains are connected and lead to the west and a storm-water retention pond. The storm water pond (surface water, was not affected). The Durham City FD and police provided initial spill and traffic control. Traffic along Renaissance Parkway was  terminated for a period of approximately five hours (between 4:00 pm and 9:00 pm on 8/24/17).     Reports were made to the NC DEQ Incident line (9:18/8-25-17/Durham was assigned) and to the National Response Center (NRC) and incident #1188362 was assigned.
column169: Driver was counseled and placed back into training. The importance of properly inspecting the hoses was stressed to all drivers.

column17: RIP GRIFFIN TRUCK SERVICE CENTER, INC.
column168: AT 10:52 AM ON 8/11/2017, A WHITE PICKUP WAS TRAVELING EAST ON C.R. 60, RIP GRIFFIN TRUCK & TRAILER WERE TRAVELING SOUTH ON SH 349. WHITE PICKUP FAILED TO YIELD RIGHT OF WAY BY TURNING RIGHT (SOUTH) ONTO SH 349 FROM C.R. 60 RIP GRIFFIN TRUCK RIGHT FRONT BUMPER CONTACTED WHITE PICKUP LEFT FRONT RESULTING IN RIP GRIFFIN DRIVER LOSING CONTROL OF TRUCK & TRAILER. RIP GRIFFIN UNITS ROLLED AT LEAST ONE TIME COMING TO REST ON IT PASSENGER SIDE FACING WEST. THE CARGO TANK WAS NOT COMPROMISED, BUT ETHANOL WAS LEAKING FROM ALL 4 TANK DOME LIDS AT AN UNDETERMINED RATE.  AT 11:31 AM ONE OF OUR OTHER DRIVERS DISCOVERED THE ACCIDENT AND CONTACTED OUR DISPATCH OFFICE, WHO THEN CONTACTED THE TRANSPORTATION MANAGER (WAYNE BARRON), & SAFETY DIRECTOR (RICHARD FARRIS). WE WERE INFORMED THAT SOMEONE HAD ALREADY CALLED 911 FOR ASSISTANCE. MR. BARRON THEN CONTACTED OUR COMPANY ENVIRONMENTAL CONSULTANT (LYNN NIEWIADOMSKI). MS. NIEWIADOMSKI CONTACTED TCEQ FOR NOTIFICATION & BULLDOG ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, FOR OUR COMPANY EMERGENCY RESPONSE AND REMEDIATION.  OUR SAFETY DIRECTOR ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 1:30 PM, AND SAW THE MIDLAND FIRE DEPT. HAD CONTAINED THE SPILL WHICH HAD RAN INTO THE DITCH ON THE EAST SIDE OF THE HWY. WITH ABSORBENT LOGS. THE FIRE DEPT. HAD ALSO SPRAY THE TANK TRAILER AND RELEASE ETHANOL WITH FOAM. OTHER RESPONDERS AT THE SCENE WERE, TXDOT, TEXAS DEPT OF PUBLIC SAFETY, CITY OF MIDLAND, & EMS.  AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 PM BULLDOG ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. THEY WITH THE HELP OF MIDLAND FIRE DEPT. DRILLED HOLES IN THE SIDES OF ALL 4 TANK COMPARTMENTS SO THAT THE REMAINING ETHANOL IN THE TANK TRAILER COULD BE PUMPED OUT PRIOR TO THE UPRIGHTING THE TRUCK & TRAILER. AFTER ALL REMAINING ETHANOL WAS PUMPED INTO ANOTHER TRAILER, AND COMPARING THE AMOUNT OF ETHANOL IN THAT TRAILER TO THE AMOUNT THAT WAS ORIGINALLY LOADED IN THE WRECKED TRAILER WE DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY 2988 GAL. OF ETHANOL HAD BEEN RELEASED.

column168: Our company driver was heading northbound on Mead Ave in Everson, WA. He approached a curve where his passenger side steer tire left the pavement and sunk into the sandy soil. He responded by turning hard to the right and hitting his brakes. the inertia of the tanks pushed his truck along and he continued to pull the left. This resulted in his truck falling on it's drivers side and his trailers fell that way as well. The hard turn caused the rear trailer to collide with the lead trailer resulting in a breach of the front drivers side seam to to rupture. Most of the spill was from the rear trailer. The product flowed quickly on the road by the curb and into the backyard of a property. The front trailer was leaking from the top loading hatch onto the road as well. The spill did not encroach any drainage. The curb leak stopped approx 100 ft from the spill. As for the yard, the product pooled in a low-laying area. The driver got out with a small laceration on his head, bruising on his arm, and a sore back. He has been treated and is seeking treatment and I on light duty until he is released to work. Emergency personnel were on scene in 10 mins. The spill was cleaned up in 4 days. An environmental study/test was performed and the property was deemed as clean.
column169: We performed a post-crash assessment with the driver/management/safety to determine what the cause was, and to consider strategies to prevent future crashes with Hazmat.     It was suggested to change the driving route  conduct further training for all drivers  assess driver skills on a regular basis.   Provide positive incentives for safe driving  In safety meetings, cover actions that can affect the employee's driving (sleep, health, exercise, etc)

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS DELIVERINIG A LOAD OF CRUDE OIL THAT HE HAD LOADED IN THE FIELD. DRIVER WAS HEADING WEST ON WELD COUNTY ROAD 120 IN COLORADO WHEN HE DRIFTED OFF OF THE LEFT SIDE OF THE ROAD AND ROLLED ¼ TURN ONTO ITS SIDE. SOMEHOW DURING THE ACCIDENT, THE RIGHT REAR OF THE TRACTORS FRAME PUNCTURED A HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER. WITH THE TRUCK AND TRAILER ON ITS SIDE THE HOLE WAS ABOVE THE FLUID LEVEL IN THE TANK TRAILER. IT LOOKED LIKE WHEN THE HOLE WAS PUNCTURED THE AMBIENT PRESSURE IN THE TANK SPRAYED THE TRAILER AND DUSTED THE GROUND. THERE WAS SOME OIL THAT SEEPED FROM THE PUNCTURE BUT WAS MINIMIZED BY RAGS AND DIAPERS. COLORADO STATE PATROL HAZMAT TEAM WAS ON SCENE AND AFTER GROUNDING FIELD WAS ESTABLISHED WE UNLOADED THE TRAILER THROUGH INSPECTION PORTS ON TOP OF THE TRAILER. WE PACKED THE PUNCTURED FULL OF WAX BEFORE TURNING THE TRUCK AND TRAILER UPRIGHT. NO OTHER CRUDE OIL WAS RELEASED FROM THE PUNCTURE. ONCE THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WHERE UPRIGHT AND MOVED OUT OF THE WAY COLORADO HAZMAT TEAM DETERMINED THAT THE SPILLAGE WAS MINIMAL AND DID NOT REQUIRED CLEANUP.   ALSO INCLUDED IN THIS REPORT IS THE HAZMAT TEAM NARRATIVE REPORT THAT STATES NO CLEAN UP NECESSARY.
column169: THIS WAS A DRIVER ERROR THAT CAUSED THE INCIDENT. THE HAZMAT RELEASE WAS MINIMAL AND WAS ADDRESSED DURING THE ENTIRE ENCOUNTER. ALL STEPS AND PRECAUTIONS WERE TAKEN TO PREVENT ANYMORE LOSS THAN AT THE INITIAL TIME THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED.
