column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: At approximately 08:00 a Univar material handler was finished with production and disconnecting a sulfuric railcar when he disconnected the 2" hose attached to railcar without closing the product valve. The pressure on the railcar was not let off or released and when the hose was removed from railcar the sulfuric shot out of the syphon tube and up the handlers chemical suit sleeves.  As the handler moved away from the stream of sulfuric his right side of his face and neck was splashed with sulfuric. The handler made to a safety shower and was under spray for 15 minutes.  Ambulance was called to the scene due to the amount of pain and burning of the handlers skin.  He was transported to University of Nebraska Medical Center where he was placed into the burn unit.  He will in the burn unit overnight and no determination on how long he will be there.   While the handler was being attended to, the sulfuric railcar was still blowing product out of the valve.  The stream was steady enough that i had shut down all air to allow the car to stop building air pressure and when it was safe the valve was closed so no more sulfuric spilled onto the ground.  The sulfuric was mostly contained on Univar site except for about 5 to 10 gallons on the dirt over the fence on Union Pacific property.  Total amounts of sulfuric spilled is approx. 700 gallons.  ESI(environmental contractors) are assisting with clean up of spill.

Norfolk Southern personnel reported a strong odor around tank car GATX37571.  Upon inspection by a contractor, the source of the odor was a vapor release from the man-way.  The cause of the release was loose manway bolts.  The man-way bolts were tightened and the car released for transport.

Upon arrival at the delivery location, a drum was found leaking on the pallet inside truck. Investigation revealed that the drum was punctured by a protruding nail from the skid it was loaded on. The remaining contents of the drum was transferred into another drum and placed into an overpack. The absorbent material used to collect the released material were also containerized for later disposal. Due to the hazard of material the package specifications were not able to be obtained.
column169: Closer inspection of the pallet for protruding nails and sharp objects would likely have prevented this release.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: A report of a gasoline odor was reported in the West Colton Rail Yard.  After an assessment of the railcar was completed it was found that there was a malfunctioning vacuum relief valve. The valve was removed and replaced with a blind flange.
column169: Relief valve was replaced with a blind flange.  Shipper was notified advised on proper shipping hazmat protocols.

column168: California Public Utilities Commission completed a random inspection in the East Rail Yard.  Upon inspection, they found the manway swing bolts were less than tool tight.  Once Union Pacific Responder arrived they found that there was a vapor releasing from the manway cover.
column169: Responders tightened the manway swing bolts and stopped the release.  Shipper was contacted and informed of the proper transportation rules and policies. (NAR 200)

column168: An odor was detected by Railroad personnel.  Upon inspection of the railcar, it was found that the manway cover gasket was deteriorated and releasing vapor.
column169: The manway gasket was replaced and stopped the release.  The Shipper was contacted and informed on the rules and polices of shipping hazmat materials by rail.  (NAR 209)

column168: Railroad personnel reported of a odor coming from the tank car.  Upon inspection, it was found that the liquid valve was open and the valve plug was less than tool tight resulting in a vapor release.
column169: The valve was closed and valve plug was tightened to stop the release.  Shipper was contacted and proper rules and policies were explained for transporting hazardous materials by rail.  (NAR 119)

column168: Railroad personnel reported that an unknown liquid was spilling out of the container.  Upon inspection, it was found that 30 five (5) gallon buckets had cracked covers and were leaking.  Later, it was determined that the containers leaked 15 gallons of liquid.
column169: Packaging was secured and properly loaded in the container.  Site remediation was completed.  Shipper was contacted and advised of proper blocking and bracing accordance to AAR Pamphlet for intermodal hazardous materials transportation.
